<div id="outline-container-org1cbb1c3" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org1cbb1c3">TAR: Compress and eXtract and view List tarball.</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org1cbb1c3">
<p>
  The <b>tar</b> command is according to the manual <i>an archiving</i> utility. It is used to store several files in a single file and to manipulate
them. 
</p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="outline-container-orgbc96428" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="orgbc96428">grep</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgbc96428">
<p>
This is where the fun begins. Its name stands from Globally search for a Regular Expression and Print matching lines, and it is one
of the oldest command command-line utilities.
</p>

<p>
Lets start by creating a text file directly from the command line. If there is a command it is not in the list that we are using here, please
recall you can always use your friend <i>man</i> or <i>apropos</i> in order to find out more details.
</p>

<p>
Lets create a small text file using cat. Provide the following lines and when you are done
type ctrl-d, which is the signal for End of File (EOF):
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">cat &gt; new_file.txt
one
two
huehueocelotl
123user
user_one
user_one_two
user_ONE_three
</pre>
</div>
</div>


<div id="outline-container-org1d758bd" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org1d758bd">Now you can use <i>grep</i> to see if the word <i>one</i> occurs in your file new_file.txt</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org1d758bd">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orga4bbeb8" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orga4bbeb8">You can use <i>grep -n</i> to additionally show the line where the word appears</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orga4bbeb8">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -n one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org0ea44a2" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org0ea44a2">You can use <i>grep -c</i> you get the number of lines the word occurs</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org0ea44a2">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -c one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org0382308" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org0382308">You can use <i>grep -v</i> you get the lines where the word does not occurs</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org0382308">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -v one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgea467a9" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgea467a9">You can use <i>grep -i</i> to ignore case</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgea467a9">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -i oNe new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgf0e7f82" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf0e7f82">You can use <i>grep -x</i> to look for an exact match</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgf0e7f82">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -x one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org2b904d7" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org2b904d7">You can use <i>grep -o</i> to look only the matched parts of the matching line</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org2b904d7">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -o one new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org04f2722" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org04f2722">You can use <i>grep -A 3</i> to look for a word plus additional number of lines</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org04f2722">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -A 3 huehueocelotl new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org7f9cc96" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="org7f9cc96">You can use <i>grep -lr</i> to print the file names of files containing a word including directories</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-org7f9cc96">
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">grep -lr user_one *
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
art_git_02.html
art_git_02.html~
#art_git_02.org#
art_git_02.org
art_git_02.org~
</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-org1a30c8d" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org1a30c8d">Sed</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org1a30c8d">
<p>
This is a Stream Editor. What? Yes, you can modify a text file on the fly! No need to waste you time
by opening a text editor to  click search and replace or things like that anymore.
</p>

<p>
Lets work with the following sample text file. Again recall that at the end you have to give
the EOF signal by typing ctl-d.
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">cat &gt; new_file.txt
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the <span style="color: #e67128;">"Wise Old Jaguar"</span>.

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal<span style="color: #ffad29; font-weight: bold;"> in</span> any linux distribution.
</pre>
</div>
</div>

<div id="outline-container-orgf633041" class="outline-3">
<h3 id="orgf633041">Search and replace</h3>
<div class="outline-text-3" id="text-orgf633041">
<p>
This examples illustrates the basic usage of the sed command.  
It will search for a text pattern  in  the file and replace it with another:
</p>


<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'s/Huehueocelotl/Linux/'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Linux is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Linux has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>


<p>
In the output we note that the change occurred in the last line of text.
</p>

<p>
Also note that the command is case-sensitive:
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'s/huehueocelotl/linux/'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In linux we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>


<p>
By default sed replaces the first occurrence of the given pattern in every line.
If we want the change to be done in all occurrences in the file we use the option <i>global</i>.
</p>
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'s/Linux/Huehueocelotl/g'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Huehueocelotl is not Unix we use Huehueocelotl.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>



<p>
We can also specify to perform the changes only on the second occurrence of the pattern in each line:
</p>
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'s/linux/Huehueocelotl/2'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the Huehueocelotl terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>



<p>
Sed can also change all occurrences of a patter from the n-th occurrence:
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'s/linux/Huehueocelotl/2g'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
Huehueocelotl has Mexican roots and its name means the "Wise Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the Huehueocelotl terminal in any Huehueocelotl distribution.
</pre>



<p>
You can also be very specific and change a string in just one line
</p>
<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-bash">sed <span style="color: #e67128;">'2 s/e/E/g'</span> new_file.txt
</pre>
</div>

<pre class="example">
Huehueocelotl is a fantastic website. In huehueocelotl we use linux.
HuEhuEocElotl has MExican roots and its namE mEans thE "WisE Old Jaguar".

We use UNIX-like operators systems and because Linux is not Unix we use Linux.
Please learn linux and the linux terminal in any linux distribution.
</pre>
</div>
